Computed tomography of portal vein thrombosis: unusual appearances and pitfalls in diagnosis. In a review of 25 cases examined by CT in whom the diagnosis of visceral vein thrombosis had been made, we encountered four cases in which problematic CT findings led to an error in diagnosis by the prospective interpreter. In one case, gas in collateral periportal veins mimicked an abscess in one case, segmentally occluded portal veins resembled dilated bile ducts